VJayanthi Eshwarputhi, an empanelled artist of the ICCR, presented a Kathak recital in the Parampara Festival, organised by the Ambalam Centre of Performing Arts. She began by offering her salutations to Siva, Vishnu and Brahma, and her gurus, to the strains of raag Bhoop. Having been trained by Pt. Birju Maharaj, Kumudini Lakhia (at Nrityagram) and Maya Rao (Bangalore) Jayanthy was a picture of grace, rhythm and balance.In her two-hour recital, Jayanthi showcased the best of nritta, abhinaya and chakkars. With &#233;lan and fluidity, she presented Thaat with rhythmic pieces such as Uthaan, Thihais, Paran and Tukkadas, depicting through nuances and gestures, characters from traditional Indian tales.The Amada or regal entry was done in Moghul style. Jayanthi was in complete control while executing the Natwari, the lightening-speed steps regulated by the sound of ghungroos.The Geetika Nayaka gat and chaal was woven around Parvati. Jayanthi regaled while bringing out Krishna's merry dancing in Brindavan with the gopikas in Raas Lila from Geet Govinda. The Ashtapadi was the tour the force of the evening. Set to ragamalika, it brought out the flavour of the lyric &#8216;Chandan Charchit, Neel Kalevarpreetam Sarvar Maane' in ragas such as Pilu, Kafi, Yaman, Jaunpuri, Desh and Malhar and in the rhythmic patterns of kaharva, dadra, and adhaa. Jayanthi became one with the character, infusing energy and emotion into the piece. Accompanying her were Pravin Rao on the tabla, Fayyaz Khan on the sarangi, Shruthi Kamath on the sitar and Shakti Dhar on the flute. Vocal support was provided by Ganesh Desai.
